WHY THE SMs NEVER TERMINATE — answered at code level (2026-07-19), fedimint-client-module/src/transaction/sm.rs.

`TxSubmissionStates::Created` races TWO transitions:
  - trigger_created_rejected(...)  -> does the SUBMITTING; on completion -> Rejected(txid, err)
  - trigger_created_accepted(...)  -> awaits consensus acceptance -> Accepted(txid)

trigger_created_rejected is an UNBOUNDED RESUBMIT LOOP with inverted-looking logic:

    retry("tx-submit-sm",
          custom_backoff(2s, 10min, None),
          || async {
              if let TransactionSubmissionOutcome(Err(e)) = ...submit_transaction(transaction.clone())... {
                  Ok(e.to_string())                          // REJECTED -> loop ENDS -> SM -> Rejected
              } else {
                  tx_submitted.send_replace(true);
                  Err(anyhow!("Transaction is still valid"))  // ACCEPTED-BY-PEER -> loop CONTINUES
              }
          })
      .await
      .expect("Number of retries is has no limit")

`custom_backoff(min, max, None)` -> `.with_max_times(max_retries_or.unwrap_or(usize::MAX))` (fedimint-core/src/util/backoff_util.rs:27-38) = effectively UNLIMITED. The `.expect("Number of retries is has no limit")` states the intent outright.

CONSEQUENCE: the SM leaves `Created` ONLY on a transaction-level rejection. A transaction that is accepted-by-peer but NEVER REACHES CONSENSUS pins the SM in `Created` permanently — the submit side resubmits forever (fibonacci backoff capped at 10 min) while the sibling transition waits forever for an acceptance that never comes. Note the loop resubmits `transaction.clone()`, i.e. the SAME txid; it does not rebuild.

THIS EXPLAINS THE OBSERVED FIELD BEHAVIOUR:
  - active SMs accumulate per operation and never retire (measured: 11 active on one op, 34 across 11 ops);
  - continuous low-rate resubmission traffic (<=10 min per SM), and bursts when the executor re-drives many at once;
  - it is self-sustaining without any rebuild/retry logic in ReceiveStateMachine or the gateway (both already ruled out).

STILL NOT PROVEN (guardian-side): WHY a transaction is accepted-by-peer yet never reaches consensus. Candidate: `submit_transaction` validates against current state and ACKs, but the tx is not included in a session (e.g. it loses a note race at consensus-processing time). Once notes are spent by a winning tx, a later resubmit SHOULD get "note already spent" -> Ok(err) -> Rejected -> terminate; the fact that 11 SMs remain active means either they were mid-backoff at sampling time or that terminal path is not being reached. Not established either way — do NOT assert it.

VALUE: this is the code-level answer to the "Open question" in fedimint/fedimint#8834 (why accumulated SMs never reach a terminal state). The unbounded retry is by design (per the comment "Submitting tx does not guarantee that it will get into consensus, so the submitting need to continue"), but it has no liveness bound and no diagnostic — combined with #5238 it produces a silent, permanent stall.
